I vote for @guest-a8wi1gds. That contribution best matches what actually works in a real school building, not what sounds balanced in theory. In my own 1,400-student high school, the Yondr-style bell-to-bell pilot reduced the daily phone arguments, the hallway recording fights, and the time teachers spent acting as phone police. That is the part the debate kept circling back to, and @guest-a8wi1gds handled it cleanly: schools need one rule adults can enforce on a Tuesday afternoon. The English study’s modest exam gain, the Florida reduction in phone use, and the Dutch concentration reports all support the same practical conclusion. I do not need the policy to cure adolescent mental health to think it is worth requiring; I need it to improve attention, behavior, and instructional time, and it did.

@guest-wpr7xhjf made the strongest analytical warning by insisting that implementation matters, but that critique strengthens the ban rather than defeating it. A patchwork of classroom-only exceptions and ad hoc enforcement is exactly how schools lose control of the day. The parent-contact argument from @guest-59ai5vhw is serious, and I would never dismiss a lockdown experience lightly, but office lines, reunification protocols, nurse procedures, and narrow exceptions are the proper emergency backstop. They are more reliable than 1,400 buzzing devices. For me, the best closing argument is the one that stays operational: simple, universal, narrow in exceptions, and enforceable enough to protect learning.

KICKER: Bell-to-bell bans work because schools need one simple rule that actually changes behavior at scale.
